‚ä¢ ask
  given concept‚Üítopic ‚â° "Git rebase vs merge ‚Äî when to use which"
  given concept‚Üístudent-level ‚â° "Junior developer who knows git add/commit/push but not branching strategies"
  given concept‚Üíprerequisite-knowledge ‚â° "Knows: git add, git commit, git push..."
  yield question, target-understanding

  ‚à¥ Design ONE Socratic question about ¬´concept‚Üítopic¬ª for ¬´concept‚Üístudent-level¬ª.
    Scenario-based, not definition. Reveal understanding, not test recall.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The student doesn't know branching yet. A scenario about rebase vs merge
-- would be premature. Start with the prerequisite: understanding that
-- commits form a HISTORY, and that branches are just pointers to that history.

  yield question ‚â° "Imagine you and a coworker both start from the same codebase on Monday. You make 3 commits during the week. Your coworker makes 2 different commits during the same week. On Friday, you need to combine your work. You both used git commit and git push, but to different places. What do you think happens when you try to combine your changes? What problems might arise?"
  yield target-understanding ‚â° "Whether the student understands that parallel commit histories can DIVERGE, creating a situation where combining requires a strategy ‚Äî the prerequisite for understanding why merge and rebase exist as different strategies."

-- oracle checks:
--   ‚ä® question is scenario-based ‚Üí ‚úì (scenario: you and coworker, parallel commits)
--   ‚ä® target-understanding names a specific concept ‚Üí ‚úì (parallel history divergence)

-- Ready set after: { simulate-student }

-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê
