-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê

‚ä¢ simulate-student
  given ask‚Üíquestion ‚â° "Imagine you and a coworker both start from the same codebase..."
  given concept‚Üístudent-level ‚â° "Junior developer who knows git add/commit/push..."
  given concept‚Üíprerequisite-knowledge ‚â° "Knows: git add, git commit, git push..."
  yield answer, confidence

  ‚à¥ Simulate this student answering. Partial knowledge, common misconceptions.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- A junior dev who knows push but not branches would reason from experience
-- with single-user workflows. They'd likely think of "conflicts" in a vague
-- file-overwriting sense, not in terms of commit graph divergence.

  yield answer ‚â° "I think when I try to push my changes, it would say there's already newer changes there? Like when you try to save a file that someone else already saved? I think git would tell me there's a conflict and I'd have to figure out which version to keep. Maybe I'd have to copy my changes somewhere, pull their changes, and then paste mine back in? I've had that happen before where git said I can't push and I had to pull first."
  yield confidence ‚â° "unsure"

-- oracle checks:
--   ‚ä® answer reflects student level ‚Üí ‚úì (vague "conflict" understanding, file-save mental model)
--   ‚ä® confidence ‚àà {"confident", "unsure", "guessing"} ‚Üí ‚úì ("unsure")

-- Ready set after: { evaluate }

-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê
-- frame 3: evaluate v0 (soft cell, LLM evaluation)
-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê

‚ä¢ evaluate
  given ask‚Üíquestion ‚â° "(parallel commit scenario)"
  given ask‚Üítarget-understanding ‚â° "parallel history divergence"
  given simulate-student‚Üíanswer ‚â° "(push rejection, file-save mental model, copy-paste workaround)"
  given simulate-student‚Üíconfidence ‚â° "unsure"
  yield correct, misconceptions[], understanding-level

  ‚à¥ Evaluate the answer. Identify specific misconceptions.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The student has PARTIAL understanding: they know push can be rejected and
-- pull is needed. But their mental model is wrong ‚Äî they think of it as
-- file overwriting, not commit graph divergence.

  yield correct ‚â° false
  yield misconceptions ‚â° [
    "FILE-SAVE MENTAL MODEL: Student thinks git conflicts are like two people saving the same file ‚Äî 'which version to keep.' Git conflicts are about combining COMMIT HISTORIES, not overwriting files. Two commits can change different files and still need combining. The student's model can't explain non-conflicting merges.",
    "COPY-PASTE RECOVERY: Student's instinct is to manually copy changes, pull, then paste back. This reveals they don't understand that git TRACKS their changes as commits ‚Äî they think their work exists only as file contents, not as a replayable sequence of changes. This misconception blocks understanding rebase (which replays commits)."
  ]
  yield understanding-level ‚â° "partial"

-- oracle checks:
--   ‚ä® correct ‚àà {true, false} ‚Üí ‚úì (false)
--   ‚ä® each misconception is specific and falsifiable ‚Üí ‚úì
--     (file-save model: falsifiable by showing non-conflicting merge)
--     (copy-paste: falsifiable by showing git stash or commit-based recovery)
--   ‚ä® understanding-level ‚àà {"none", "partial", "solid"} ‚Üí ‚úì ("partial")
--   ‚ä® if correct then misconceptions empty ‚Üí ‚úì (vacuous: not correct)
--   ‚ä® if understanding-level = "solid" then correct ‚Üí ‚úì (vacuous: not solid)

-- understanding-level = "partial" ‚âÝ "solid" ‚Üí ‚ä¢‚àò continues
