-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê

‚ä¢‚ä¢ spawn-remedials
  given evaluate‚Üímisconceptions ‚â° [
    "FILE-SAVE MENTAL MODEL: ...",
    "COPY-PASTE RECOVERY: ..."
  ]
  yield ¬ßremedial-cells[]

  ‚à¥ Create a remedial cell for each misconception.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The spawner creates two remedial cell definitions, one per misconception.

  yield ¬ßremedial-cells ‚â° [
    "‚ä¢ remedial-file-save-model
      given misconception ‚â° \"Git conflicts are like two people saving the same file\"
      yield counter-example, corrected-understanding

      ‚à¥ Show the student a scenario where two people change DIFFERENT files
        in the same repo. Person A edits README.md, person B edits main.py.
        They both commit and push. Git combines both changes with NO conflict.
        Ask: if git conflicts were about file-saving, why did this work?
        The answer: git tracks CHANGES PER FILE, not the whole project as one
        file. Conflicts happen only when the SAME lines in the SAME file diverge.

      ‚ä® counter-example involves changes to different files
      ‚ä® corrected-understanding mentions per-file change tracking",

    "‚ä¢ remedial-copy-paste-recovery
      given misconception ‚â° \"To recover from push rejection, copy files, pull, paste back\"
      yield counter-example, corrected-understanding

      ‚à¥ Show the student: you have 3 commits. Git KNOWS about all 3 as
        separate, replayable changes. When push is rejected, 'git pull'
        doesn't erase your work ‚Äî it COMBINES your 3 commits with the remote's
        commits. Your commits are safe because git stored them, not because
        you copied files. Demonstrate: 'git log' shows your commits are still
        there after a failed push. Ask: why would you copy files if git
        already saved every commit?

      ‚ä® counter-example shows commits surviving failed push
      ‚ä® corrected-understanding mentions commits as durable, replayable units"
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ‚ä® ¬ßremedial-cells has same length as misconceptions ‚Üí ‚úì (2 remedials, 2 misconceptions)
--   ‚ä® each addresses exactly one misconception ‚Üí ‚úì

-- Spawned cells join the frontier but are NOT evaluated in this trace ‚Äî
-- they await future students who exhibit these misconceptions.
