  ‚à¥ Confirm per-file tracking. Bridge: merge (new commit) vs rebase (replay).

  yield question ‚â° "Good news: you're right that changing different files doesn't cause conflicts! Git tracks changes per-file, per-line. Now here's the real question: you have 3 commits (A, B, C) and your coworker has 2 commits (X, Y). Git gives you two ways to combine them. Option 1 (merge): git creates a NEW commit 'M' that has BOTH your history and theirs ‚Äî like a knot tying two ropes together. Your history looks like: A-B-C-M and X-Y-M. Option 2 (rebase): git takes YOUR commits and REPLAYS them on top of theirs ‚Äî so the history looks like: X-Y-A'-B'-C' (where A', B', C' are copies of your commits). Which do you think would be easier to understand when reading the history later? Why?"
  yield target-understanding ‚â° "Whether the student can reason about commit history TOPOLOGY ‚Äî merge preserves parallel history (shows what actually happened), rebase linearizes it (cleaner but rewrites commits). This is the core of when-to-use-which."

