  given concept‚Üítopic
  given concept‚Üístudent-level
  given concept‚Üíprerequisite-knowledge
  yield question, target-understanding

  ‚à¥ The student thinks rebase is always better. Design a scenario that
    BREAKS this assumption. Three developers share a branch. Developer A
    rebases, changing commit hashes. Developers B and C pull and get
    DUPLICATE commits ‚Äî the old hashes AND the new ones. Ask the student:
    what went wrong? Why did rebase cause problems HERE but not in the
    earlier example? Guide toward the rule: rebase local/unpushed work,
    merge shared branches.

  ‚ä® question is scenario-based, not a definition request
  ‚ä® target-understanding names a specific concept being tested"

-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê
-- ‚ä¢‚àò ITERATION 3 ‚Äî the shared-branch trap
