-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê

‚ä¢ ask
  given concept‚Üítopic ‚â° "Git rebase vs merge ‚Äî when to use which"
  given concept‚Üístudent-level ‚â° "Junior developer..."
  given concept‚Üíprerequisite-knowledge ‚â° "..."
  yield question, target-understanding

  ‚à¥ Scenario: shared branch rebase causes duplicate commits.

  yield question ‚â° "You said you'd always use rebase. Let me give you a scenario: you, Alice, and Bob all work on the same branch called 'feature.' You've all pushed commits to it. You decide to rebase the feature branch onto main to get a cleaner history. After you push, Alice pulls and says: 'Why are there duplicate commits? I see my commit twice ‚Äî once with its original hash and once with a new hash!' What happened? And does this change your mind about always using rebase?"
  yield target-understanding ‚â° "Rebase REWRITES commit hashes. On shared branches, this creates duplicates for anyone who already has the old commits. The student should realize rebase is safe only for LOCAL, UNPUSHED commits ‚Äî the rule is 'rebase local, merge shared.'"

-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê
-- frame 17: simulate-student v3 (soft cell)
-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê

‚ä¢ simulate-student
  given ask‚Üíquestion ‚â° "(shared branch rebase, Alice sees duplicates)"
  given concept‚Üístudent-level ‚â° "Junior developer..."
  given concept‚Üíprerequisite-knowledge ‚â° "..."
  yield answer, confidence

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The student now has the visual model (linear vs branching history)
-- and is confronted with a failure scenario. Junior devs can reason
-- about this with the A'/A hash-rewriting hint from the previous question.

  yield answer ‚â° "Oh! Because when I rebased, my commits got new copies ‚Äî like you said, A becomes A' with a different hash. But Alice already had the original A. So when she pulls, git sees A and A' as two different commits because the hashes don't match, even though the changes are the same. So she gets both... that's bad. OK so I think I get it now ‚Äî you should only rebase if nobody else has your commits yet? Like if I haven't pushed yet, I can rebase safely because nobody has the old hashes. But if the branch is shared, use merge because it doesn't rewrite anything. Is that right?"
  yield confidence ‚â° "confident"

