-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê‚ïê

‚ä¢= obs-adaptive-questioning
  yield observation
  ‚ä¢= observation ‚Üê "QUESTIONS ADAPTED TO MISCONCEPTIONS: the ‚à¥ block evolved from a generic scenario (v0: parallel work) to targeted probes (v1: different files to break file-save model, v2: visual merge vs rebase, v3: shared-branch trap to break rebase-always). Each rewrite addressed the SPECIFIC misconception from evaluate. The teacher never repeated a question type ‚Äî each round's question was diagnostically targeted. This is the difference between Socratic teaching and quizzing: questions are DESIGNED to reveal, not just test."

‚ä¢= obs-misconception-accumulation
  yield observation
  ‚ä¢= observation ‚Üê "‚ä¢‚ä¢ SPAWNER ACCUMULATES REMEDIAL CELLS: 4 remedial cells spawned across 4 iterations, each targeting a specific misconception. These cells are ARTIFACTS of the teaching process ‚Äî a misconception library that grows monotonically. Future students who exhibit the file-save misconception can be routed directly to remedial-file-save-model without re-deriving the remedial from scratch. The ‚ä¢‚ä¢ spawner turns teaching into curriculum generation."

‚ä¢= obs-simulated-student-realism
  yield observation
  ‚ä¢= observation ‚Üê "SIMULATED STUDENT TRACKS LEARNING: v0 answer was vague (file-save model). v1 answer wavered (model cracking). v2 answer was confidently wrong (rebase always better). v3 answer was correctly derived (rebase local, merge shared). The confidence trajectory (unsure‚Üíunsure‚Üíconfident-wrong‚Üíconfident-right) mirrors real learning: confusion ‚Üí dawning ‚Üí overgeneralization ‚Üí correction. The simulate-student cell's ‚à¥ block didn't change ‚Äî the QUESTIONS changed, and the student's responses naturally tracked the teaching progression."

‚ä¢= obs-prerequisite-discovery
  yield observation
  ‚ä¢= observation ‚Üê "THE TEACHER DISCOVERED PREREQUISITES DYNAMICALLY: the initial question was about parallel work (prerequisite), not rebase vs merge (target topic). The teacher's ‚à¥ block detected that the student lacked prerequisite knowledge and adjusted downward. This is ADAPTIVE DIFFICULTY: the ‚ä¢‚àò loop's evaluate cell detected understanding-level and design-followup adjusted accordingly. The spec says 'if none: simpler question, if partial: target misconception, if solid: advance.' The evaluate‚Üídesign-followup pipeline implements automatic difficulty scaling."

‚ä¢= obs-evolution-vs-spawning
  yield observation
  ‚ä¢= observation ‚Üê "‚ä¢‚àò AND ‚ä¢‚ä¢ SERVE DIFFERENT ROLES IN THE SAME PROGRAM: ‚ä¢‚àò evolves the ask cell (the question adapts). ‚ä¢‚ä¢ spawns remedial cells (the misconception library grows). Evolution is the TEACHING LOOP ‚Äî same cell, improving. Spawning is ARTIFACT GENERATION ‚Äî new cells, accumulating. They compose naturally: each ‚ä¢‚àò iteration may trigger ‚ä¢‚ä¢ to spawn new remedials. The teaching process BOTH adapts (‚ä¢‚àò) and accumulates (‚ä¢‚ä¢) simultaneously."

‚ä¢= obs-student-derives-rule
  yield observation
  ‚ä¢= observation ‚Üê "THE STUDENT DERIVED THE RULE, NOT THE TEACHER: in iteration 3, the student said 'you should only rebase if nobody else has your commits yet... if the branch is shared, use merge.' The teacher never STATED this rule ‚Äî the scenario (shared-branch rebase causing duplicates) forced the student to INFER it. This is genuinely Socratic: the teacher designs experiences, the student extracts understanding. Cell's structure makes this visible: the rule appears in simulate-student‚Üíanswer, not in ask‚Üíquestion."
